```bash
sudo npm install -g n8n
```

there are a few alternatives, depending on why you want to avoid it.

---

### **1. Install n8n without `-g` (local project install)**

This keeps it in a local folder instead of system-wide:

```bash
mkdir ~/n8n_local && cd ~/n8n_local
npm init -y
npm install n8n
npx n8n
```

Here `npx n8n` runs it without needing a global install.

---

### **2. Use `pnpm` or `yarn` instead of npm**

```bash
sudo npm install -g pnpm
pnpm add -g n8n
```

or

```bash
sudo npm install -g yarn
yarn global add n8n
```

---

### **3. Install from source with curl + npm**

```bash
git clone https://github.com/n8n-io/n8n.git
cd n8n
npm install
npm run build
./packages/cli/bin/n8n
